<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Manual"><PMID Version="1">20409381</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2010</Year><Month>07</Month><Day>30</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2022</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>21</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1080-6059</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>16</Volume><Issue>5</Issue><PubDate><Year>2010</Year><Month>May</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Emerging infectious diseases</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Emerg Infect Dis</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Dengue virus surveillance for early warning, Singapore.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>847</StartPage><EndPage>849</EndPage><MedlinePgn>847-9</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.3201/eid1605.091006</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>In Singapore, after a major outbreak of dengue in 2005, another outbreak occurred in 2007. Laboratory-based surveillance detected a switch from dengue virus serotype 1 (DENV-1) to DENV-2. Phylogenetic analysis showed a clade replacement within DENV-2 cosmopolitan genotype, which accompanied the predominant serotype switch, and cocirculation of multiple genotypes of DENV-3.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Lee</LastName><ForeName>Kim Sung</ForeName><Initials>KS</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Environmental Health Institute, Singapore .</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Lai</LastName><ForeName>Yee Ling</ForeName><Initials>YL</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Lo</LastName><ForeName>Sharon</ForeName><Initials>S</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Barkham</LastName><ForeName>Timothy</ForeName><Initials>T</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Aw</LastName><ForeName>Pauline</ForeName><Initials>P</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Ooi</LastName><ForeName>Peng Lim</For